{"slug": "witch", "root": "witch", "category": "profession", "gloss": "a practitioner of witchcraft", "definition": "A witch is a practitioner of witchcraft — folk and ritual magic, healing or harming — historically and unjustly imagined as bound in pact to the Devil. One of the oldest magic-words in English, and among the most contested.", "history": "Old English had *wicce* (feminine) and *wicca* (masculine), beside the verb *wiccian*, 'to work magic'; the deeper root is genuinely uncertain, perhaps tied to 'bending' or to 'sacred rite.' The word's darkest chapter is early-modern — the trials that killed tens of thousands, powered by manuals like the *Malleus Maleficarum* (1487). Modern scholarship (Thomas, Cohn, Ginzburg, Hutton) dismantled the myth of a real witch-cult, and 20th-century Wicca reinvented the witch as a chosen, positive identity.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Bosworth–Toller, s.v. wicce", "where": "Classical lexica"}, {"label": "Ronald Hutton, The Triumph of the Moon", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Norman Cohn, Europe's Inner Demons", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Old English wicce (fem.) / wicca (masc.), akin to wiccian ‘to practise magic’", "first": "attested before 1000", "note": "One of the oldest magic-words in English, and one of the murkiest — its pre-history is genuinely uncertain, perhaps tied to a root for ‘to bend’ or ‘sacred rite.’", "hook": "The word older than the witch trials.", "lang": "Old English"}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 46, "oracle_total": 13, "in_flavor_cards": 45, "in_oracle_cards": 10, "name_match_count": 65, "by_variant": {"witch": 47, "witches": 11, "witchcraft": 1}, "first_year": 1994, "colors": {"R": 20, "W": 14, "C": 6, "B": 62, "G": 14, "